                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 511. 4A1/914.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chargé <persName type="from">Hibben</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Hague</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1910-11-10">
                            <hi rend="italic">November 10, 1910</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Mr. Hibben says the minister for foreign affairs informs him that the proposals
                    of Great Britain relative to a preliminary study of morphine and cocaine
                    conditions were not included in opium conference invitation, but that a
                    supplementary note embodying them will be sent at once. Mr. Hibben states that
                    the minister for foreign affairs said also that he had not been advised that the
                    acceptance of British Government depended upon the action taken on the British
                    proposals, and asks if he shall formally so advise him.</p>
            </div>
